								<div itemprop="articleBody">
		<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><b>Penetrating Cone Fracture Rock Breakage.</b></p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Tradename of "SunBurst" from Australia.&nbsp; State of the art, non-explosive chemical rock breakage technology for close proximity excavation applications in mining and civil engineering.</p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">Explosive system, cycle time of 6 mins, giving 0.33 m3 each explosion.</p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">A typical rate of 10 No cycles per hour, giving 3.3 m3/hr/rig.</p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;">However, tests have shown differing results...</p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><b>Fresh granite of class 1 strengt</b>h - One hole in the floor, yielding 0.15 m3 of rock.&nbsp; If more holes had been injected, a yield of 0.5 - 1.0 m3 would be expected.</p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><b>Moderately fresh igneous rock of class 2 strength&nbsp;</b>- Three holes in a sloping trench, in adjacent locations, yielding 2.6 m3 of rock for each hole.</p>
<p align="-webkit-auto" style="font-size: medium; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 19px; color: #333333; font-family: tahoma, verdana, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><b>Moderately weathered volcanic rock of class 3 strength&nbsp;</b>- Two holes in the floor, in separate locations, yielding 1.2 - 1.5 m3 of rock for each hole.</p> 	</div>

	
